** An estimated 75,000 rubles per hectare of forested area in 1993 prices, 
by analogy with UN data, as the minimum fire damage figure used in 
estimates in foreign countries. 


  The active protection of forests from fire is conducted on 
an 
area of 770 million* hectares. The biggest fire zones in 1992 
were in the forests of the Sakha Republic (Yakutia)--305,000* 
hectares, and Amur Oblast--135,000* hectares. 
  As a result of fires in past years, large areas of dry trees 
were recorded in Tyumen Oblast (24,500 ha) and Irkutsk Oblast 
(12,000 ha) in 1992. For that same reason, areas of dead trees 
per 1,000 hectares of wooded area were 3.44 hectares in 
Kaliningrad Oblast, 4.15 ha in Leningrad Oblast, and 5.52 ha in 
Vladimir Oblast. 
  The area of forests dying as a result of adverse external 
factors has been increasing in the last three years (353,500* ha 
in 1990, 595,500* ha in 1991, and 543,600* ha in 1992). The 
largest areas of trees killed by industrial emissions are 
located in the environs of the Norilsk Combine, where these 
areas increased by 61,300 hectares in 1992 alone. The 
dessication and degradation of forests on an area of 90,000 
hectares was recorded within the exposure zones of the 
Severonikel and Pechenganikel combines in Murmansk Oblast, and 
all of the trees in the forests covering an area of 15,000 
hectares here are dead. 
  The increasingly severe radioactive pollution of these 
forests is alarming. Zones of pollution by radionuclides were 
recorded in the forests of 15 oblasts, and the Chernobyl 
accident alone was responsible for this kind of damage on an 
area equivalent to 1.3 million hectares. 
  Zones of forest pests and diseases, which also cause the 
dessication and death of trees, covered an area of 2.9 million* 
hectares in 1992. In the West Siberian Economic Region, for 
example, desiccated trees in the zones of forest insect pests 
(the sudden mass proliferation of the Siberian silkworm moth) 
represented 60 percent of the total area of dead forests. 
Measures were taken to combat forest pests and diseases on an 
area of 486,000* hectares in 1992. 
  In the past five years the death of trees and the practice 
of 
clear-cutting have resulted in the loss of 13 million hectares 
of wooded area. Furthermore, reforestation (measured in terms of 
the final stage) has been carried out on an area of only 6.9 
million hectares, or 52.9 percent. In 1992 reforestation 
projects were launched on an area of 1.402 million* hectares, 
and saplings were reclassified as commercial timber on 1.426 
million* hectares. Burned-out forests and dead trees cover a 
total area of 26.5 million hectares in the Russian Federation. 
  The improvement of the state of RF forests will require 
immediate measures to manage forest resources more efficiently, 
protect the forests, and secure their intelligent use. This 
could be promoted by the adoption and implementation of state 
reforestation and fire protection programs and the passage of 
new forest laws. 
  Experts have said that Russia's flora is in a disastrous 
state, but the absence of inventories of plant resources and 
facilities (with the exception of forests) precludes objective 
appraisals of the situation in the country as a whole and in 
different regions. 
<H3>  1.7. Flora and Fauna and Their Present State, Use, and 
Protection </H3>
<H5>  Flora </H5>
  The state of natural plant communities in the arid 
cis-Caspian zone is alarming. The uncontrolled growth of 
anthropogenic influences and the inefficient use of the land, 
without adequate reclamation, have caused the degeneration of 
native plants and the degradation and destruction of the 
vegetative ground cover on large areas. The natural plant 
communities of the steppes and meadows are being diminished, and 
the area of deteriorating tundra communities is increasing. 
  In spite of the somewhat stabilized area of the forests, as 
one type of vegetation, their qualitative indicators have 
declined, and the area covered by dessicated and dead trees has 
increased in some regions. 
  Plant communities are damaged during reclamation projects. 
The broad-scale drainage of wooded areas, for example, has 
impoverished the gene pool of many unique marsh plant 
communities. In particular, whole groves of marshwort were lost 
in Ivanovo Oblast. 
  The unfounded and unofficial procurements of medicinal herbs 
and other useful plants are cause for serious concern, 
particularly the gathering of these plants by cooperatives and 
private entrepreneurs. This has led to the intensive depletion 
of stocks of wild flora and the destruction of plant communities 
that took centuries to become established. In the North Caucasus 
this practice has undermined reserves of ramson (bear's onion), 
in Moscow Oblast the supply of male fern is being depleted, in 
Ivanovo Oblast the stocks of common valerian and bistort have 
been reduced, and in Krasnodar Kray the common St. John's wort 
and yarrow have become rare species. 
  The ground cover is being damaged by the unwarranted 
authorization of gardening and vegetable farming on territories 
with unique plant communities and in forest preserves, 
sanctuaries, and natural monuments. This has occurred in 
Krasnodar Kray, Moscow Oblast, and several other Russian oblasts. 
  The degradation of the plant cover as a whole has been 
accompanied by additions to the list of species in danger of 
extinction, or endangered plants. The RF Red Book now contains 
information on 533 species of flora requiring protection in the 
country: 440 angiospermae (flowering), 11 gymnospermae, 10 
ferns, 4 lycopsids, 22 mushrooms, 29 lichens, and 17 fungi. 
Several species of plants have completely disappeared. In recent 
years, for example, the king fern (Krasnodar Kray), the Volga 
cinquefoil (Central Cis-Volga), the mercury squill (Far East), 
and many others were registered as extinct species. 
  The problem of preserving the specific diversity of flora 
can 
only be solved by securing the proper protection of the habitats 
of species, plant communities, and natural ecosystems. The 
number of species of vascular plants in different 
botanical-geographic regions is illustrated in Figure 1.7.1. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-36A>           Figure 1.7.1. Number of Species of </FIG>



  The stability of terrestrial ecosystems was evaluated within 
the framework of the ``Russia's Ecology'' program, with a view 
to the indicators of supplies of living biological matter and 
dead organic substances, phytoproductivity, specific diversity, 
and the mosaic patterns of the vegetative cover (Figure 1.7.2). 
The use of an integral index of the stability of terrestrial 
ecosystems can secure consideration for the distinctive features 
of the natural component during the planning of regional 
resource use strategy. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-37A>           Figure 1.7.2. Integral Assessment of </FIG>



  The fundamentals of RF legislation on flora must be adopted 
without delay and the planning of a state policy and its 
implementation through the appropriate programs will be required 
for the establishment of the economic and legal basis for the 
intelligent use and protection of plant resources. 
<H5>  Fauna and the State of Habitats </H5>
  The abundance and specific diversity of Russia's fauna 
depend 
directly on the quality of animal habitats. There are three 
separate categories of territories with fairly distinct 
characteristics, depending on the degree of transformation 
resulting from economic activity. 
  The first category is the territory with developed industry 
and agriculture and high population density. The Central and 
Central-Chernozem regions, the cis-Volga, the Volga-Kama zone, 
the North Caucasus, the Urals, and the cis-Ural region belong to 
this category. Here the ratio of forests and open spaces has 
reached the critical level, predetermining considerably 
diminished fauna with a lack of balance in numbers and in specie 
composition. The disruption of the fragile ecological balance in 
these regions could have the most unpredictable results, ranging 
from the loss of certain species to the possibility of a 
dramatic increase in their numbers and outbreaks of various 
epizootic diseases. 
  The second group consists of territories of intensive 
development, industrial construction, the rapid growth of 
extractive branches, and the establishment of a new economic 
structure. The group includes the northern zone of the ETR, the 
new industrial and agricultural zones of Siberia and the Far 
East, and the regions of the West Siberian gas and oil fields, 
where the deterioration of wildlife habitats is still localized. 
This is primarily connected with logging, plowing, hydraulic 
engineering, reclamation, the direct pollution of soil, water, 
and plants with petroleum products, and the agitation and stress 
caused by hunting. 
  The third group consists of territories with a traditional 
economic structure, virtually untouched by change. These are the 
vast expanses in the Siberian north and east, the northeastern 
part of the ETR, and the Far East. The state of fauna here is 
relatively stable because the economy is geared directly to the 
use of animal resources. 
  The main strategic objective in the stabilization of the 
specific composition and numbers of fauna in the next few years 
consists in determining the allowable areas and parameters of 
human activity in protected seats of biodiversity, which include 
wetlands in highly developed regions and regions of average 
development, the floodplains of the same regions and of 
hydraulic engineering construction sites; territories where 
endemic species of animals are concentrated (Maritime Kray, 
Sakhalin Island, and the North Caucasus); sections of the steppe 
in zones of widespread agricultural development. Measures should 
also be taken without delay for government protection and 
monitoring of animals in the logging regions of Siberia and the 
European north and in zones of gas and oil production. 
<H5>  Animal Resources and Their Use and Protection </H5>
  Invertebrates are distinguished by the highest number of 
species (around 80,000) and the lowest level of our knowledge of 
the distribution and numbers of individual species. The most 
vulnerable invertebrates are the fauna groups of the European 
plains and oak woods, some parts of Lake Baykal, the Caspian 
Sea, and other large bodies of water, the groups of Caucasian 
cave-dwellers, and those associated with certain types of flora 
and mountain peaks. Habitat deterioration and excessive fishing 
have reduced the numbers of certain species and have led to the 
imposition of bans on fishing for scallops, crab, sea cucumber, 
trepan, and mussels in some parts of Maritime Kray and the Black 
Sea. Stocks of fresh-water invertebrates--crayfish, pearl 
oysters, river oysters, and medicinal leeches--have been 
diminished perceptibly by the same factors. The RF Red Book now 
lists 34 species of insects and 15 species of mollusks. 
  Among vertebrates, the amphibian class is represented by 
only 
24 species in the Russian Federation, and the Ussuriysk clawed 
newt, the Asia Minor newt, the Caucasian frog, and the rush toad 
are listed in the Russian Red Book. There are no reliable data 
on the numbers of amphibians. Each year up to 500,000 lake frogs 
are caught for export, and 200,000-300,000 grass frogs and 
leopard frogs are trapped for medical and biological 
institutions. 
  Reptiles achieve maximum diversity and numbers in the arid 
and semi-arid oblasts. For example, 21 of the 69 species 
recorded in the Russian Federation live in limited sections of 
the European south of Russia, and there are only 1-7 species in 
the rest of the ETR and in most of Siberia. All species of 
reptiles and amphibians are trapped and kept as pets. The 
underground trade in these species cannot be estimated at this 
time, but their constantly rising prices arouse serious concern 
about the state of their populations. The virtually unrestricted 
operations of the private firms that sprang up in the last few 
years for the production of poisons pose a genuine threat to the 
future of even a species as ubiquitous as the common adder. 
Eleven species of reptiles are listed in the RF Red Book. 
  The distribution of varieties of ornithological species in 
different Russian territories is illustrated in Figure 1.7.3. 


<FIG ID=JPRS-TEN-005-38A>           Figure 1.7.3. Total Number of Species </FIG>



